author: nobodywasishere
body: This seems like a problem with the upstream package [mach](https://pypi.org/project/mach/), which hasn't been updated with the [latest version](https://github.com/bolucat/Firefox/tree/master/python/mach) of mach in the Firefox source code, which (after a quick look) has [fixes](https://github.com/bolucat/Firefox/blob/870b30b7c207435654882f036e666beba67ee861/python/mach/mach/main.py#L19) for these issues.

author: jdm
body: I asked whether the Firefox build developers could publish a new version, but they recommend vendoring the current package and cherry-picking/fixing whatever is blocking us. That's the path I intend to follow.

author: jdm
body: Once #28648 merges, we'll be able to apply any fixes necessary to support new python versions inside `python/mach/mach`.

There's another work-around described here:
https://firefox-source-docs.mozilla.org/setup/macos_build.html#macos-sdk-is-unsupported

My question is, where should the mozconfig file be placed to specify the SDK path?
And setting the MOZCONFIG environment var to the location of the mozconfig does not work (?!)

author: jdm
body: The supported workaround for servo is setting the MACOS_SDK_PATH environment variable to point to a supported SDK: https://github.com/servo/mozjs/blob/ef986b1a2c23081fe4d37aeaab5323d3dec033f3/makefile.cargo#L14 . A supported one can be acquired from https://github.com/phracker/MacOSX-SDKs.

```
lld-link: error: could not open 'msvcrt.lib': no such file or directory
```
but I can give the full, very long output if it's necessary.
I have tried using both the 64 and 32 bit version of LLVM, and linking LLVM in .cargo/config.toml. What am I doing wrong? I've never heard of LLVM so I'm not familiar with how it thinks. Some cursory google searching only revealed problems with VS specifically, but I'm using VSCode and the same thing happens when I run it in powershell. This also happens with both the python and the mach.bat, although that shouldn't be the issue, seeing as mach.bat simply runs the python script.

author: negator
body:
~It may be fixed now.~  Those wpt tests pass locally.

The issue was that the body needs to be streamed as a separate parallel task, otherwise we attempt to stream the entire payload at once. Which, in the case of an eventsource, may never end.

https://github.com/servo/servo/blob/66cad685b8447abdb10b22dc81e13bafdd339572/components/net/http_loader.rs#L1869


We also need to yield to allow the body streaming future to start:
https://github.com/servo/servo/blob/66cad685b8447abdb10b22dc81e13bafdd339572/components/net/http_loader.rs#L1916


***EDIT*: It appears some websites are hanging when they did not previously, so it appears there is still an issue here. This is not ready for testing yet.**

author: lemmabit
body:
I think the CSS test failures are more interesting than the WPT ones.

I'm not sure why `/_mozilla/css/text_overflow_basic_a.html` is failing. It fails when I run it with `test-wpt` on my machine, too, but when I actually open it and its reference up in Servo and compare the pixels myself (using GIMP), they're identical.

The other two WPT failures are due to `<input>` elements with no content shrinking vertically. Empty inputs were one of the few places where empty text fragments were generated before my changes. It turns out that in order to be correct, empty text fragments in most cases must function as if they weren't there. Making that change broke empty `<input>`s. I'm not sure of the best way to fix this break.

author: mbrubeck
body:
The code looks good.  Thank you!

I'm not sure why the test is failing, but one possible difference when rendering to an image versus a window could be if the layout changes after something triggers a reflow, so that the output is different depending on exactly when a snapshot is taken.  Or it could be a difference in fonts (our test harness makes certain fonts like Ahem available), though that doesn't seem likely to be the problem in this case.

author: lemmabit
body:
@mbrubeck Indeed, if I trigger a reflow by adding this after the `<section>`:

```html
<script>
document.getElementsByTagName('section')[0].offsetParent;
</script>
```

The output in the generated PNG becomes correct. `document.body.offsetParent` doesn't work, though.

author: emilio
body:
The crates.io version isn't even the servo/ version, it's the servo version with the `MallocSizeOf` stuff removed, IIRC.

I used to keep the Servo version periodically up-to-date, though I haven't done so in a while (I probably should).

author: devongovett
body: Ah. How does the crates.io version get updated? Is there another repo?

author: cortesi
body: I have a project that relies on selectors, and the lack of updates to the crates.io package is making things a bit harder than they need to be. We are also a little concerned that development momentum in servo has petered out, and that the bits we rely on might stagnate. I wonder if it's time to consider extracting selectors into a free-standing module that would be easier to move forward?

author: CYBAI
body:
@jdm I found it seems it's not so easy to setup the environment to git push from `servo/servo` to `servo-wpt-sync/servo` from https://github.com/servo/servo/pull/28369.

So, I wonder if it's possible to have a repo (or just the servo repo) under `servo-wpt-sync` account; then, we setup a nightly cronjob in `servo-wpt-sync`'s repo to do this nightly sync. But, we will need a nightly branch and make it as the default branch because currently GitHub Actions only support running cronjob on **default** branch. (or, should we give `servo-wpt-sync` permission to create branches to `servo/servo`?)

Also, I'm wondering if we should create a secret for `servo-wpt-sync`'s GPG key so that we can make sure its commit is verified 🤔 

If this solution sounds plausible, I think the patch of `--always-succeed` for `python/servo/testing_commands.py` in  #28369 should be merged into this repo (`servo/servo`) so that we can avoid throwing exit 1 while executing the command in downstream.

author: mateon1
body:
I tried to triage this with saved samples I have, but I can't seem to get a recent version of servo running, as they segfault or panic in graphics bindings, even in headless mode. This would be a good issue to debug over IRC if that still existed, not sure where servo devs gather nowadays.

I have a couple reduced samples that used to trigger the same panic, with a slightly different stack trace (Caused by JS DOM modification, not HTML parsing), and other unreduced samples that are too big to share.

Unfortunately I believe the original bug in this issue may have depended on network behavior or something like misbehaving ads. In hindsight I wish I captured some WARCs that could be replayed.

I think it's safe to close this issue and reopen, or open another if this reoccurs.
